{"title_page": "The Longaberger Company", "text_new": "{{short description|American manufacturer and distributor of handcrafted maple wood baskets}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = The Longaberger Company\n| native_name      = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name   = \n| trading_name     = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| logo             = \n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = Newark-ohio-longaberger-headquarters-front.jpg\n| image_size       = 200px\n| image_caption    = Longaberger's old headquarters building, modeled on a giant Longaberger Medium Market Basket\n| type             = Public\n| traded_as        =JRJR \n| predecessor      =CVSL \n| successor        = \n| founder          =Dave Longaberger \n| defunct          = {{End date|2018}} \n| fate             = Liquidated\n| industry         = \n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| products         = Baskets, vitrified pottery, wrought iron, wood crafts and other products for the home.\n| brands           = \n| production       = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           =JRJR Networks \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.longaberger.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| former_name      = \n| former type      = \n| foundation       = <!-- Dresden, Ohio, USA ({{Start date|1973|01|01}}) -->\n| location_city    = [[Frazeysburg, Ohio|Frazeysburg]], [[Ohio]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| locations        = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| bodystyle        = \n}}\n\n'''The Longaberger Company''' is an American [[manufacturer]] and distributor of handcrafted [[maple]] wood [[basket]]s and other home and lifestyle products. Its old corporate headquarters on Ohio's [[State Route 16 (Ohio)|State Route 16]] is a local landmark and a well-known example of [[novelty architecture]], since it takes the shape of the company's biggest seller, the \"Medium Market Basket\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluffton.edu/~sullivanm/longa/longa.html|title=Longaberger Company Home Office|last=Sullivan|first=Mary Ann|publisher=Art History Webmaster Association|accessdate=January 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIt was one of the primary employers in the area near [[Dresden, Ohio]]; at its peak in 2000, it employed more than 8,200 people and had $1 billion in sales.  Founded in Dresden, the company moved to [[Newark, Ohio]]. A family-owned and operated business, the Longaberger Company was started by [[Dave Longaberger]] in 1973.\nLongaberger used [[multi-level marketing]] to sell products. The company had about 45,000 independent distributors (called Home Consultants) in the United States who sold Longaberger products directly to customers. The iconic building is a 160-scale of the company's medium market basket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/longaberger-basket-building-hotel-ohio/index.html|title=Basket-shaped building to become a luxury hotel|first=Marnie |last=Hunter|website=CNN|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1919, J.W. Longaberger accepted an [[apprenticeship]] with The Dresden Basket Factory. Although the Dresden Basket Factory closed during the [[The Great Depression|Great Depression]], Longaberger continued to make baskets on the weekends. He and his wife Bonnie Jean (Gist) Longaberger eventually raised enough money to purchase the closed basket factory and start a business of their own.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longaberger.com/companyHistory.aspx|title=The History of The Longaberger Company|author=The Longaberger Company|date=n.d.|publisher=The Longaberger Company|accessdate=January 8, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOne of J.W. and Bonnie's children, Dave, opened J.W.'s Handwoven Baskets in 1973. Starting in 1978, the company began selling Longaberger baskets through home shows using a multi-level marketing model. Each basket was handmade, signed, and dated by the maker.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}\n\nA combination of a recession and changing tastes in home decor combined to send sales, which peaked in 2000 at $1 billion, to about $100 million in 2012.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Tim |first1 = Feran |url = http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/business/2013/04/25/longaberger-new-owner-seeking-more-direct-sales-companies.html |title = Longaberger's new owner intends to fill basket with more direct-sales companies |work = [[The Columbus Dispatch]] |date = April 25, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the company was taken over by [[JRJR Networks|CVSL, Inc]].\n\nIn May 2015, Tami Longaberger, who had led the company since her father died in 1999, resigned as chief executive officer and director of the company.<ref>{{cite news |last1 = Mallett |first1 = Kent |title = Tami Longaberger resigns as company CEO |url = http://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2015/05/05/tami-longaberger-resigns-company-ceo/26910415/?hootPostID=336856e520de6295d958a2e5aa0ad512 |accessdate = May 5, 2015 |work = Newark Advocate |date = May 5, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, the company said it would sell the Basket Building and move its employees to Longaberger's factory in [[Frazeysburg, Ohio|Frazeysburg]], Ohio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whio.com/news/news/national/iconic-longaberger-headquarters-close/nqY6q|title=Iconic Longaberger headquarters to close|date=February 27, 2016|publisher=[[WHIO-TV]]|location=Dayton, OH|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160228131309/http://www.whio.com/news/news/national/iconic-longaberger-headquarters-close/nqY6q/|archivedate=February 28, 2016|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 27, 2016|agency=Cox Media Group National Content Desk}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2016, there were fewer than 75 full-time and part-time employees; about 30 of those still made baskets.\n\nOn May 4, 2018, a note was sent out from a sales force supervisor that the company had ceased operations.<ref>{{Cite news |url = http://www.dispatch.com/business/20180504/longaberger-story-coming-to-end |title = Longaberger said to have gone out of business |last = Feran |first = Tim |work = The Columbus Dispatch|access-date = May 4, 2018  |language = en }}</ref>\n\nThe Longaberger brand was revived in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url = https://www.dispatch.com/business/20191113/longaberger-brand-to-live-again-on-qvc |title = Longaberger brand to live again on QVC |last = Weiker |first = Jim |work = The Columbus Dispatch|date = November 13, 2019|access-date = November 14, 2019  |language = en }}</ref>\n\n== Basket Building ==\nThe seven-story, 180,000-square-foot building was designed by The Longaberger Company, and executed by [[NBBJ]] and Korda Nemeth Engineering. The building opened in 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.longaberger.com/homeOfficeFacts.aspx |title = Longaberger Facts & Features |author = The Longaberger Company |date = n.d. |publisher= The Longaberger Company |accessdate = November 26, 2012 }}</ref> The basket handles weigh almost 150 tons and can be heated during cold weather to prevent ice damage.<ref>{{cite book |last = Zurcher |first = Neil |year = 2008 |title = Ohio Oddities |edition = 2nd |location = Cleveland |publisher = Gray & Company |isbn = 978-1-59851-047-8 }}</ref> Originally, Dave Longaberger wanted all of the Longaberger buildings to be shaped like baskets, but only the headquarters was completed at the time of his death.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}  The company stopped paying property taxes on the building at the end of 2014.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2016/07/08/longaberger-empties-famous-basket-building-next-week/86852322/|title=Longaberger empties famous basket building next week|last1=Mallett|first1=Kent|date=July 8, 2016|work=Newark Advocate|accessdate=July 13, 2016}}</ref> Workers moved out in 2016.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn December 2017, the building was purchased by Steve Coon, a [[Canton, Ohio]]\u2013based developer who owns Coon Restoration, and his partner, Bobby George, of Cleveland.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newarkadvocate.com/story/news/local/2017/12/29/longaberger-basket-sale-finalized/990406001/|title=A 'big vision' in store for Longaberger basket building|last1=Bruner|first1=Bethany|date=December 29, 2017|work=The Newark Advocate|access-date=February 25, 2018|last2=DeVito|first2=Maria|language=en}}</ref> By November 2018, the pair had put it up for sale.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dispatch.com/news/20181127/giant-longaberger-basket-building-again-for-sale|title=Giant Longaberger Basket Building Again For Sale|last=Feran|first=Tim|date=November 27, 2018|work=The Columbus Dispatch|access-date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, the building had not sold and Coon announced plans to turn the building into a luxury hotel and has been working toward having the building added to the National Register of Historic Places.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/longabergers-big-basket-building-be-turned-hotel-owner-says-2019-oct|title=Longaberger's Big Basket building to be turned into hotel, owner says|date=October 21, 2019|website=WBNS-10TV Columbus, Ohio {{!}} Columbus News, Weather & Sports|language=en|access-date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 20, 2019, Heritage Ohio \u2013 the state's official [[historic preservation]] organization \u2014 held the first tour of the building since its 2016 closing as part of fundraising efforts. More that 600 people participated. Executive director Joyce Barrett said, \u201cPeople were in tears and hugging each other\u201d because \"they were so happy to be back in the Basket.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atlasobscura.com/articles/longaberger-basket-building-hotel|title=The Strange Second Life of Ohio's 'Big Basket' Building|last=Imbler|first=Sabrina|date=November 5, 2019|website=Atlas Obscura|language=en|access-date=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|The Longaberger Company}}\n*{{official website|http://www.longaberger.com}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080112070353/http://travel.discovery.com/tv/ratzenberger-america/goods/longaberger.html The Travel Channel \"John Ratzenberger's Made In America\".]\n*[http://www.worldcollectorsnet.com/longaberger/ World Collectors Net Longaberger Information and Message Board]\n\n{{coord|40|3|49|N|82|20|48|W|type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n{{Multi-level marketing}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Longaberger Company}}\n[[Category:Novelty buildings in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Newark, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Direct selling]]\n[[Category:Multi-level marketing companies]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies disestablished in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American manufacturer and distributor of handcrafted maple wood baskets}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = The Longaberger Company\n| native_name      = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. If there is more than one native name, in different languages, enter those names using {{tl|lang}}, instead. -->\n| romanized_name   = \n| trading_name     = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| logo             = \n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = Newark-ohio-longaberger-headquarters-fro